Use plain exported domain functions as the default extraction pattern. In this codebase, routes are supposed to be thin orchestrators, and your own guidance already says so explicitly: extract route business logic into domain-layer functions and “follow the existing module’s export pattern (functions, not classes)” in [agents.md](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/agents.md:200) and [god-handler-extraction-requires-domain-function-pattern.md](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/docs/solutions/logic-errors/god-handler-extraction-requires-domain-function-pattern.md:19). The strongest concrete example is the explore session flow: the route stays focused on auth, parsing, analytics, and responses, while reusable business steps live in [packages/core/src/lib/backend/feeds/session.ts](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/packages/core/src/lib/backend/feeds/session.ts:338).

So the pattern I’d recommend is:

1. Route file stays minimal.
   It should only do method wiring, auth, request/body/path parsing, domain calls, and response formatting. Your split route example at [apps/tma/src/app/api/user/[userId]/book/status/route.ts](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/apps/tma/src/app/api/user/[userId]/book/status/route.ts:1) is the right shape.

2. Per-method handler file if HTTP logic is non-trivial.
   If a route has enough HTTP-specific work, split into `handlers/getX.ts`, `postX.ts`, etc., like [apps/tma/src/app/api/feedback/route.ts](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/apps/tma/src/app/api/feedback/route.ts:1). That keeps App Router files tiny without pretending HTTP orchestration is domain logic.

3. Backend domain module with exported functions for reusable business flows.
   Put the actual use-case steps in the module that owns the data/behavior, like `@backend/feeds/session`, `@backend/feedback`, etc. Prefer functions such as `resolveSessionCity`, `resolveDistanceFilter`, `fetchCityContext` over introducing a new class for each route-sized use case.

I would not introduce “service classes” as the general rule. In this repo, classes exist, but they are exceptions for areas with strong invariants and multiple related mutations, not the baseline style. `BookMutationService` is justified because it centralizes a dangerous invariant across many callers and is protected by an ESLint rule; see [packages/core/src/lib/backend/domain/BookMutationService.ts](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/packages/core/src/lib/backend/domain/BookMutationService.ts:41). `UserBanService` and `UserActivityService` are similar: cohesive multi-method lifecycle owners. That is different from “this route got long, so let’s make a service class.”

A practical rule set:

- Use plain functions when extracting logic from one or two routes, especially read/compute/orchestrate flows.
- Use a class only when you have a true domain subsystem with multiple related operations sharing private helpers and invariants across many callers.
- Do not create a class just to wrap a single `execute()` method. That adds ceremony without buying you anything in a Prisma/Next codebase that already works well with module functions.

If you want a concrete house style, I’d standardize on this:

```ts
// route.ts
export const { POST } = createRouteHandler({ POST: postThingHandler });

// handlers/postThing.ts
export async function postThingHandler(req: NextRequest) {
  const user = await authenticateRequest(req);
  const input = await parseThingRequest(req);
  const result = await createThing({ userId: user.id, input });
  return jsonResponse(req, result);
}

// lib/backend/things.ts
export async function createThing(params: CreateThingParams): Promise<CreateThingResult> {
  // business rules, queries, transactions, side effects
}
```

That matches your repo better than a class-heavy application-service layer.

